                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-11-27</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>i'm NOT a religious person, and i think that's why i LOVE this book because he's a living example of how you can be SPIRITUAL but not RELIGIOUS. you can believe in God and not be religious. a lot of people don't understand this. however, this was the first autobiography i read (i read it like 3 years ago), and i was very, very impressed. this book is very powerful, life changing, spiritual, helpful, educational and entertaining. now i always thought Mase was cool as a rapper (i was never a FANATIC like a lot of my other peers) but i must say i like him better as a pastor. when he came back to rap i was very dissapointed because he conradicts EVERYTHING about rap in this book. he said he was young and bitter when he wrote this book, well i say write another book because if you read this book NOW (after he came back to rap) you wouldn't like Mase at all anymore, because you'd be confused, misled and angry. so i do reccommend this book for it's power (and it's secrets on Camron, Foxy Brown, Puffy, 112 and an unkown stripper who Mase discovered.....EVE!!) but i DON'T reccommend it because it's conradicting everything he stands for today. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Mase vs. Pastor Mason Betha</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      /
                      <span>2</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-10-08</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I give it 5 stars 'cause it's was the best that he put out. The reason why he retired from hip-hop 'cause he had to get his mind focused. So he asked God to be his guidance. I was basically felt everything where he go to in life incl. starting out as a rappper and then a minister. Y'know Mase would be talkin' 'bout a lot of things that goin' on in our world right now. (i.e. Hip-Hop has lost its culture, too many people dying and getting killed, what's the difference between secular rap vs. sacred rap, I mean Good rap vs. Bad rap. Simple. I proud of Mase for what he did and I hope for that he put out another album that'll be entitled "Karma" (which he'll be workin' on w/ help from the Neptunes producing that album.) I read it supposed to drop out next year. So hopefully it will be good and make sure it's not the last. Well anyway, long story, Lemme put this down. Here some messages on which I quote down the book which I put down as my favorites.
<br />
<br />Here are they:
<br />
<br />"The best rap music is the most arrogant, with the most demonic message. How can you mix that with God?" pg. 76
<br />
<br />"People say they want to reach young people so they have to use music that young people want to listen to. What happens when young people want to listen to pimps? Do we make gospel pimps? You're trying to change God to fit what the people want. What got you saved? The Bible says God doesn't change." pg. 76
<br />
<br />"It's sad to say it but Biggie died for rap, but rap sure didn't die for Biggie. Christ is the only thing you should be dying for, because He's the only one who was willing to die for you. Dying for rap? That ain't the move. That just shows you to be real careful what you put your faith in and what you say you're willing to die for-- becuase of what you speak into creation happens. There is so much power into the tongue." pg. 62
<br />
<br />If you like to learn more about this, read over some scriptures on which I read off the Bible (i.e. Phillipians 4:8, Romans 12:1-2, 2 Cor 5:17-21, 2 Tim 2:22, 1 Tim 5:22, Acts 2:38,40, etc.)just to help you understand
<br />I'm not saying you can't listen to rap or whatever, but keep that in mind you have to be alert on what you say and how you bring a message to people. That's how I did it.
<br />
<br />But you can still listen to hip-hop as long you don't condemn it or whateva, 'cause what happen is that people would get into the wrong message of saying things that would offend people y'know what I mean? Hip-Hop has to be about culture, life, 'bout love, honor, respect, and spirituality. All types of things.
<br />
<br />But as long as you keep loving God and thanking Him for your spirit, love and everything, you know he'll follow Him. Yeah always believe that. 'cuz to me I love God and I thank Him each day for giving me the power to help people.
<br />
<br />and Pastor Mase, I luv you and hope you continue to do your thing man 'cuz i'm a big supporter. I don't care what people say about you. But you keep doin' your thing, aight?
<br />
<br />Anyway, I highly recommend this book to those who want to read more about Mase and want to follow his footsteps that he is. 'cuz His album "Welcome Back" which he put out in Aug of this year is off da chain man. Ya'll gotta go cop his album and especially his entire book. I believe that he is taking hip-hop to another level like Kanye West (who is my favorite rapper to date) trying to change what hip-hop should be in the near future. 
<br />
<br />Peace I'm out and may God bless.
<br /></span>
                  
